Visualization in R

Lizzie Kumar & Isha Raut
April 2, 2018

ggplot2

  • Library in R that makes nice graphics
  • Makes creation of good looking, useful graphics much easier than base R
  • Consistent with a grammar of graphics

ggplot2

Plot = Data + Aesthetics + Geometric Objects

Definitions: Aesthetics

Mapping of information to a visual property

  • Categorical -> Color
  • Numerical -> Position
  • …

Definitions: Aesthetics

Mapping of information to a visual property

  • Categorical -> Color
  • Numerical -> Position
  • Categorical -> Shape
  • Numerical -> Color
  • Numerical -> Size
  • Numerical -> Transparency
  • …

Definitions: Geoms

A geometric object

  • Point
  • Line
  • …

Definitions: Geoms

A geometric object

  • Point
  • Line
  • Bar
  • Box-and-whisker
  • Polygon
  • …

A typical ggplot2 call & translation

ggplot(flights, aes(x = dep_delay, y = arr_delay)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

We pass data into the ggplot function, add geoms separated by +, and specify aesthetics with aes()

Basic Plots

  • Scatter Plot
  • Line Chart
  • Bar Chart
  • Histogram
  • Density Plot
  • Box Plot

Initialization

  • Initialize empty graphic
  • We will add our plot to this base plot
  • Feed base plot data, x and y values

Initialization Continued

plot <- ggplot(flights, aes(x = dep_delay, y = arr_delay))
plot

We have specified aesthetics, but haven't added any geoms! Tip: Specify aesthetics in the main ggplot call to keep the mapping consistent across different geoms

Scatter Plot

plot + geom_point()

Scatter Plot Continued

plot + geom_point(aes(color = factor(origin)))

We can also add aesthetic mappings for individual geoms using aes()

Scatter Plot Continued

plot + geom_point(color = 'blue', size = 5, shape = 25, alpha = .01)

We can hard-code values within geoms by passing them in as arguments WITHOUT using aes()

Scatter Plot Continued

plot + geom_point(aes(size = distance, shape = factor(origin)), color = 'blue')

Line Chart

plot + geom_point() + geom_smooth()

Some geoms do statistical transformations on the data that can be further configured

Line Chart Continued

plot + geom_point() + geom_smooth(span = .01)

Line Chart Continued

plot + geom_point() + geom_smooth(span = .9)

Line Chart Continued

plot + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm')

Line Chart Continued

plot + geom_point() + geom_smooth(aes(color = factor(origin)), method = 'lm')

Box Plot

plot2 <- ggplot(flights, aes(distance, air_time))
plot2 + geom_boxplot()

Box Plot Continued

plot2 + geom_boxplot(fill = 'lightblue', colour = 'black')

Box Plot Continued

plot2 + geom_boxplot(outlier.colour = 'red', outlier.shape = 25)

Box Plot Continued

plot2 + geom_boxplot(aes(color = factor(origin)))

Bar Chart

plot <- ggplot(flights, aes(carrier))
plot + geom_bar()

Bar Chart Continued

plot + geom_bar(aes(weight = arr_delay))

Bar Chart Continued

plot + geom_bar(aes(fill = factor(origin)))

Bar Chart Continued

plot + geom_bar(aes(fill = factor(origin)), position = 'dodge')

Bar Chart Continued

plot + geom_bar(aes(fill = factor(origin)), position = 'fill')

Histogram

plot <- ggplot(flights, aes(arr_delay))
plot + geom_histogram()

Histogram Continued

plot + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5)

Histogram Continued

plot + geom_histogram(bins = 100)

Histogram Continued

plot + geom_histogram(aes(fill = factor(origin)))

Histogram Continued

plot + geom_histogram(aes(color = factor(origin)))

Density Chart

plot + geom_density()

Density Chart Continued

plot + geom_density(adjust = .01)

Density Chart Continued

plot + geom_density(adjust = 100)

Density Chart Continued

plot + geom_density(aes(color = factor(origin), fill = factor(origin)))

Density Chart Continued

plot + geom_density(aes(color = factor(origin), fill = factor(origin)), position = 'stack')

Density Chart Continued

ggplot(flights, aes(arr_delay, ..count.., color = factor(origin),
                    fill = factor(origin))) +
  geom_density(position = 'stack')

Some additional options

  • ... + xlim(c(1, 10)) + ylim(c(50, 100): crop X and/or Y axis
  • ... + facet_wrap(~carrier): make subplots by factor value

Finishing Touches

ggplot(flights, aes(arr_delay)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  xlim(c(-50, 300)) +
  facet_wrap(~origin, scales = 'free_y') +
  ylab('Count') + xlab('Delay') +
  ggtitle('Number of Delayed Flights by Origin') +
  theme_minimal()

Use ggsave(filename) to save the most recently displayed plot to a file!

Plotly and ggplot

  • Open source tools that allows interactibe graphics
  • Has a function to neatly convert ggplots to inteactive plots class: small-code
library("plotly")
ggflights<- ggplot2::ggplot(flights, aes(arr_delay, ..count.., colour=factor(origin),fill = factor(origin))) + geom_density(position='stack')

Basic Map

plot <- ggplot(data, aes(long, lat))
plot + geom_polygon(aes(group=group, fill=median_rent))

More Complex Maps

plot +
  # add outlines
  geom_polygon(aes(group=group, fill=median_rent),
               colour='black', size = .2, alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_gradient2()

More Complex Maps

plot +
  geom_polygon(aes(group=group, fill=median_rent),
               colour='black', size = .2, alpha = 0.5) +
  # add new color information
  scale_fill_gradient2(midpoint = median(data$median_rent),
                       limits=c(min(data$median_rent),
                                max(data$median_rent)),
                       low='red', mid='white', high='blue')

More Complex Maps
